Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C and put the #kettle{} on to boil. Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into roughly 1⁄2cm pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve, then remove the core from the @bell pepper{1} and cut into 1⁄2cm slices. Trim the tops from the @green beans{150%g} and chop into 2cm lengths. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all). Zest the @lemon{1}, then cut it into wedges.

Pour the boiling @water{400%ml} into a #measuring jug{} and add the @chicken stock powder{1} and @saffron{1} powder. Stir to dissolve. Add some @olive oil{2%tbsp} to a large ovenproof #saucepan{} on medium-high heat (if you don't have one, use a normal saucepan and transfer to an #ovenproof dish{} later). Fry the @diced chicken thigh{140%g} until browned, turning regularly, ~{5-7%minutes}. Add the onion, and cook until soft, ~{5%minutes}.

Add the pepper, green beans, garlic and @smoked paprika{1%tsp} to the pan. Cook for ~{1%minute} more, then add the @arborio rice{175%g}. Stir to coat in the oil and spice. Add the stock and bring the mixture to the boil (then transfer to an ovenproof dish if necessary). Cover with a #lid{} (or #foil{}) and cook on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{20-25%minutes}.

> TIP: Check after 20 mins to see if the rice is cooked and the liquid absorbed.

Place the @sea bream fillets{2} in a #mixing bowl{} and add half the lemon zest, a glug of oil and a pinch of @salt{}. Rub the flavours into the skin and flesh of the fish, then set aside. In a #small bowl{}, mix the remaining lemon zest with the parsley and stir in the olive oil. Squeeze in the juice of half the lemon wedges. Season with @salt{} to taste and set aside.

Twelve mins into the rice's cooking time, put a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil). Once hot, carefully lay in the sea bass fillets, skin-side down. Cook until the edges begin to brown and the skin is crispy, ~{3-4%minutes} - don't move them during this time, then turn and cook for ~{2-3%minutes} on the other side.

> IMPORTANT: The fish is cooked when the centre is opaque.

Remove your pan from the heat.

When the rice is ready, remove it from your oven and leave to cool for a couple of minutes. Taste and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} if needed. Share between your #bowls{}, top with the sea bass and spoon over the parsley and lemon oil. Serve with the remaining lemon wedges to squeeze over at the table. Enjoy!